an as they appear in works raning from Robert Rogers' Ponteach, or The Savages of America (1766) to Robertson Davies' 'Pontiac and the Green Man' (1977), demonstrating how English-Canadian writers have illuminated their own world through reference to Indian culture. The Indian has been seen as an antagonist, as a superior alternative, as a member of a vanishing and lamented race, and as a hero and the source of the new myths. Although white/Indian tension often lies in apparently irreconcilable opposites, Monkman finds in the literature surveyed complementary images reflecting a common humanity.This is an important contribution to a hitherto unexplored area of Canadian literature in English which should give rise to further elaboration of this major theme.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCanadian literature (English)xHistory and criticismxCanadaxCriticism, interpretation, etcxHistory. 0aCanadian literaturexHistory and criticismxCriticism, interpretation, etc.zCanadaxHistory. 0aCanadian literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aIndians in literature. 0aIndians of North AmericaxHistoryxCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericazCanadaxHistory. 0aIndiens d'Amérique dans la littérature. 0aIndiens d'AmériquexHistoirezCanada. 0aIndiens d'Amérique dans la littérature. 0aIndiens d'AmériquexHistoirexCanada. 0aLittérature canadienne-anglaisexHistoire et critique. 0aLittérature canadienne-anglaisexHistoire et critique. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Archive 1933-1999z978311049094740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148758584640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487585846423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487585846.jpg  a978-3-11-049094-7  University of Toronto Press eBook-Pack